text:
Willow Street, east side, at, adjoining and south of Middagh Street. Also seen are Nos. 24-26 Middagh Street, at and adjoining the S.E. corner of Willow Street. This corner building (No. 24), was a chop house in 1815. In 1836 it was the residence of Oliver Hutchinson. In 1922 a Mrs. Griswald owned it.

April 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

1-5 Middagh Street, north side, west of No. 5, at right foreground. Also seen is No. 62 Columbia Heights, (built in 1850 by the Rev. J. Carter), to the left of which is a Park.

24-32 Middagh Street, south side, between Willow and Hicks Streets. The corner house was a chop house in 1815. It became a residence in 1836.

Federal Art Project, "Changing New York," photographs by Berenice Abbott.
May 14, 1936

Poplar Street, west from and including Hicks Street, to Columbia Heights. Skyscrapers of lower Manhattan are seen in the background. A, "Roulston" chain store is seen at the S.W. corner of Hicks and Poplar Streets.

April 1, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

Poplar Street, west from Willow Street to Columbia Heights, where it terminates. The 3-story house, in the center, is on the latter street. In the background is the lower Manhattan skyline, the buildings (from left to right) being the City Bank Farmers Trust, the Bank of Manhattan and the 60 Wall Tower.

About 1939
